# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dbus-ipc
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] The freedesktop.org project also developed a free and open-source software library called libdbus, as a reference implementation of the specification.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] This library is not D-Bus itself, as other implementations of the D-Bus specification also exist, such as GDBus (GNOME), QtDBus (Qt/KDE), dbus-java and sd-bus (part of systemd).
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] D-Bus is an inter-process communication (IPC) mechanism initially designed to replace the software component communications systems CORBA and DCOP, used by the GNOME and KDE Linux desktop environments respectively.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] The components of these desktop environments are normally distributed in many processes, each providing only one or a few *services*.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] These services may be used by regular client applications or by other components of the desktop environment to perform their tasks.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Large groups of cooperating processes demand a dense mesh of individual communication channels (using one-to-one IPC methods) between them.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] D-Bus simplifies the IPC requirements with one single shared channel.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] D-Bus provides a software-bus abstraction that gathers all the communications among a group of processes over a single shared virtual channel.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Processes connected to a bus do not know how it is internally implemented, but the D-Bus specification guarantees that all processes connected to the bus can communicate with each other through it.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] D-Bus incurs at least a 2.5x performance loss over one-to-one IPC.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] A process can connect to any number of buses, provided that it has been granted access to them.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] In practice, this means that any user process can connect to the system bus and to its current session bus, but not to another user's session buses, or even to a different session bus owned by the same user.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] The latter restriction may change in the future if all sessions of a user are combined into a single user bus.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] D-Bus provides additional or simplifies existing functionality to the applications, including information-sharing, modularity and privilege separation.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] For example, information on an incoming voice call received through Bluetooth or Skype can be propagated and interpreted by any currently running music player, which can react by muting the volume or by pausing playback until the call is finished.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] D-Bus can also be used as a framework to integrate different components of a user application.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] For instance, an office suite can communicate through the session bus to share data between a word processor and a spreadsheet.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Every connection to a bus is identified in the context of D-Bus by what is called a *bus name*.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] There are two types of bus names: *unique* and *well-known*.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] A well-known bus name consists of two or more dot-separated strings of letters, digits, dashes, and underscores—a reverse domain name.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] An example of a valid bus name is `org.freedesktop.NetworkManager`.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] When a process sets up a connection to a bus, the bus assigns to the connection a special bus name called *unique connection name*.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Bus names of this type are immutable—it is guaranteed they will not change as long as the connection exists—and, more importantly, they cannot be reused during the bus lifetime.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] This means that no other connection to that bus will ever have assigned such unique connection name, even if the same process closes down the connection to the bus and creates a new one.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Unique connection names are easily recognizable because they start with the otherwise forbidden colon character.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] An example of a unique connection name is `:1.1553` (the characters after the colon have no particular meaning).
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] A process can ask for additional bus names for its connection, provided that any requested name is not already being used by another connection to the bus.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] In D-Bus parlance, when a bus name is assigned to a connection, it is said the connection *owns* the bus name.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] In that sense, a bus name cannot be owned by two connections at the same time, but, unlike unique connection names, these names can be reused if they are available: a process may reclaim a bus name released—purposely or not—by another process.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] The idea behind these additional bus names, commonly called *well-known names*, is to provide a way to refer to a service using a prearranged bus name.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] For instance, the service that reports the current time and date in the system bus lies in the process whose connection owns the org.freedesktop.timedate1 bus name, regardless of which process it is.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Bus names can be used as a simple way to implement single-instance applications (second instances detect that the bus name is already taken).
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] It can also be used to track a service process lifecycle, since the bus sends a notification when a bus name is released due to a process termination.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Because of its original conception as a replacement for several component oriented communications systems, D-Bus shares with its predecessors an object model in which to express the semantics of the communications between clients and services.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] The terms used in the D-Bus object model mimic those used by some object oriented programming languages.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] That does not mean that D-Bus is somehow limited to OOP languages—in fact, the most used implementation (libdbus) is written in C, a procedural programming language.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] In D-Bus, a process offers its services by exposing *objects*.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] These objects have *methods* that can be invoked, and *signals* that the object can emit.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Methods and signals are collectively referred to as the *members* of the object.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Any client connected to the bus can interact with an object by using its methods, making requests or commanding the object to perform actions.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] For instance, an object representing a time service can be queried by a client using a method that returns the current date and time.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] A client can also listen to signals that an object emits when its state changes due to certain events, usually related to the underlying service.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] An example would be when a service that manages hardware devices—such as USB or network drivers—signals a "new hardware device added" event.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Clients should instruct the bus that they are interested in receiving certain signals from a particular object, since a D-Bus bus only passes signals to those processes with a registered interest in them.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] A process connected to a D-Bus bus can request it to *export* as many D-Bus objects as it wants.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Each object is identified by an *object path*, a string of numbers, letters and underscores separated and prefixed by the slash character, called that because of their resemblance to Unix filesystem paths.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] The object path is selected by the requesting process, and must be unique in the context of that bus connection.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] An example of a valid object path is `/org/kde/kspread/sheets/3/cells/4/5`.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] However, it is not enforced—but also not discouraged—to form hierarchies within object paths.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] The particular naming convention for the objects of a service is entirely up to the developers of such service, but many developers choose to namespace them using the reserved domain name of the project as a prefix (e.g. /org/kde).
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Every object is inextricably associated to the particular bus connection where it was exported, and, from the D-Bus point of view, only lives in the context of such connection.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Therefore, in order to be able to use a certain service, a client must indicate not only the object path providing the desired service, but also the bus name under which the service process is connected to the bus.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] This in turn allows that several processes connected to the bus can export different objects with identical object paths unambiguously.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] An *interface* specifies members—methods and signals—that can be used with an object.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] It is a set of declarations of methods (including its passing and returning parameters) and signals (including its parameters) identified by a dot-separated name resembling the Java language interfaces notation.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] An example of a valid interface name is `org.freedesktop.Introspectable`.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Despite their similarity, interface names and bus names should not be mistaken.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] A D-Bus object can *implement* several interfaces, but at least must implement one, providing support for every method and signal defined by it.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] The combination of all interfaces implemented by an object is called the object *type*.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] An emitted signal, on the other hand, must always indicate to which interface it belongs.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] The D-Bus specification also defines several standard interfaces that objects may want to implement in addition to its own interfaces.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Although technically optional, most D-Bus service developers choose to support them in their exported objects since they offer important additional features to D-Bus clients, such as introspection.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] The D-Bus specification defines a number of administrative bus operations (called "bus services") to be performed using the /org/freedesktop/DBus object that resides in the org.freedesktop.DBus bus name.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Each bus reserves this special bus name for itself, and manages any requests made specifically to this combination of bus name and object path.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] The administrative operations provided by the bus are those defined by the object's interface org.freedesktop.DBus.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] These operations are used for example to provide information about the status of the bus, or to manage the request and release of additional *well-known* bus names.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] D-Bus was conceived as a generic, high-level inter-process communication system.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] To accomplish such goals, D-Bus communications are based on the exchange of *messages* between processes instead of "raw bytes".
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] D-Bus messages are high-level discrete items that a process can send through the bus to another connected process.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Messages have a well-defined structure (even the types of the data carried in their payload are defined), allowing the bus to validate them and to reject any ill-formed message.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] In this regard, D-Bus is closer to an RPC mechanism than to a classic IPC mechanism, with its own type definition system and its own marshaling.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Every D-Bus message consists of a header and a body.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] The header is formed by several fields that identify the type of message, the sender, as well as information required to deliver the message to its recipient (destination bus name, object path, method or signal name, interface name, etc.).
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] The body contains the data payload that the receiver process interprets—for instance the input or output arguments.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] All the data is encoded in a well known binary format called the *wire format* which supports the serialization of various types, such as integers and floating-point numbers, strings, compound types, and so on, also referred to as marshaling.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] The D-Bus specification defines the wire protocol: how to build the D-Bus messages to be exchanged between processes within a D-Bus connection.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] However, it does not define the underlying transport method for delivering these messages.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Most existing D-Bus implementations follow the architecture of the reference implementation.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] They can use it to exchange messages directly.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] In this scenario bus names are not required.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] They can exchange messages sending them to the message bus process, which in turn will deliver the messages to the appropriate process.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] In this scenario bus names are mandatory to identify the destination process.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] The libdbus library (or its equivalent) internally uses a native lower-level IPC mechanism to transport the required D-Bus messages between the two processes in both ends of the D-Bus connection.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] D-Bus specification does not mandate which particular IPC transport mechanisms should be available to use, as it is the communications library that decides what transport methods it supports.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] For instance, in Unix-like operating systems such as Linux libdbus typically uses Unix domain sockets as the underlying transport method, but it also supports TCP sockets.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] The communications libraries of both processes must agree on the selected transport method and also on the particular channel used for their communication.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] This information is defined by what D-Bus calls an *address*.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Unix-domain sockets are filesystem objects, and therefore they can be identified by a filename, so a valid address would be `unix:path=/tmp/.hiddensocket`.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Both processes must pass the same address to their respective communications libraries to establish the D-Bus connection between them.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] An address can also provide additional data to the communications library in the form of comma-separated `key=value` pairs.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] This way, for example, it can provide authentication information to a specific type of connection that supports it.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] When a message bus daemon like dbus-daemon is used to implement a D-Bus bus, all processes that want to connect to the bus must know the *bus address*, the address by which a process can establish a D-Bus connection to the central message bus process.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] In this scenario, the message bus daemon selects the bus address and the remainder processes must pass that value to their corresponding libdbus or equivalent libraries. dbus-daemon defines a different bus address for every bus instance it provides.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] These addresses are defined in the daemon's configuration files.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Two processes can use a D-Bus connection to exchange messages directly between them, but this is not the way in which D-Bus is normally intended to be used.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] The usual way is to always use a message bus daemon (i.e. dbus-daemon) as a communications central point to which each process should establish its point-to-point D-Bus connection.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] When a process—client or service—sends a D-Bus message, the message bus process receives it in the first instance and delivers it to the appropriate recipient.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] The message bus daemon may be seen as a hub or router in charge of getting each message to its destination by repeating it through the D-Bus connection to the recipient process.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] The recipient process is determined by the destination bus name in the message's header field, or by the subscription information to signals maintained by the message bus daemon in the case of signal propagation messages.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] The message bus daemon can also produce its own messages as a response to certain conditions, such as an error message to a process that sent a message to a nonexistent bus name.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] dbus-daemon improves the feature set already provided by D-Bus itself with additional functionality.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] For example, *service activation* allows automatic starting of services when needed—when the first request to any bus name of such service arrives at the message bus daemon.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] This way, service processes neither need to be launched during the system initialization or user initialization stage nor need they consume memory or other resources when not being used.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] This feature was originally implemented using setuid helpers, but nowadays it can also be provided by systemd's service activation framework.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Service activation is an important feature that facilitates the management of the process lifecycle of services (for example when a desktop component should start or stop).
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] D-Bus was started in 2002 by Havoc Pennington, Alex Larsson (Red Hat) and Anders Carlsson.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] The version 1.0—considered API stable—was released in November 2006.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Heavily influenced by the DCOP system used by versions 2 and 3 of KDE, D-Bus has replaced DCOP in the KDE 4 release.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] An implementation of D-Bus supports most POSIX operating systems, and a port for Windows exists.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] In GNOME it has gradually replaced most parts of the earlier Bonobo mechanism.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] One of the earlier adopters was the (nowadays deprecated) Hardware Abstraction Layer.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] HAL used D-Bus to export information about hardware that has been added to or removed from the computer.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] The usage of D-Bus is steadily expanding beyond the initial scope of desktop environments to cover an increasing amount of system services.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Another heavy user of D-Bus is Polkit, whose policy authority daemon is implemented as a service connected to the system bus.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Although there are several implementations of D-Bus, the most widely used is the reference implementation *libdbus*, developed by the same freedesktop.org project that designed the specification.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] However, libdbus is a low-level implementation that was never meant to be used directly by application developers, but as a reference guide for other reimplementations of D-Bus (such as those included in standard libraries of desktop environments, or in programming language bindings).
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] The freedesktop.org project itself recommends applications authors to "use one of the higher level bindings or implementations" instead.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] GDBus is an implementation of D-Bus based on GIO streams included in GLib, aiming to be used by GTK+ and GNOME.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] GDBus is not a wrapper of libdbus, but a complete and independent reimplementation of the D-Bus specification and protocol.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] MATE Desktop and Xfce (version 4.14), which are also based on GTK+ 3, also use GDBus.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] In 2013, the systemd project rewrote libdbus in an effort to simplify the code, but it also resulted in a significant increase of the overall D-Bus performance.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] In preliminary benchmarks, BMW found that the systemd's D-Bus library increased performance by 360%.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] By version 221 of systemd, released in 2015, the sd-bus API was declared stable.
[src:dbus-ipc/d-bus] Several programming language bindings for D-Bus have been developed, such as those for Java, C#, Ruby, Rust and Perl.
[src:dbus-ipc/freedesktop-org] The project was founded by Havoc Pennington, a GNOME developer working for Red Hat in March 2000.
[src:dbus-ipc/freedesktop-org] Widely used open-source Desktop projects, such as GNOME, KDE's Plasma Desktop, and Xfce, are collaborating with the freedesktop.org project.
[src:dbus-ipc/freedesktop-org] In 2006, the project released Portland 1.0 (xdg-utils), a set of common interfaces for desktop environments. freedesktop.org joined the X.Org Foundation in 2019.
[src:dbus-ipc/freedesktop-org] Some of the project's servers are hosted by Portland State University.
[src:dbus-ipc/freedesktop-org] freedesktop.org provides hosting for a number of relevant projects.
[src:dbus-ipc/freedesktop-org] Also, Avahi (a free Zeroconf implementation) started as a fd.o project but has since become a separate project.
[src:dbus-ipc/freedesktop-org] Besides the variables mentioned below, XDG BDS also specifies that users' local binary files may be installed into `$HOME/.local/bin`.
[src:dbus-ipc/freedesktop-org] Systems compliant with the spec are expected to make this directory available in their CLI's `PATH` environment variable.
[src:dbus-ipc/freedesktop-org] The project aims to catch interoperability issues much earlier in the process.
[src:dbus-ipc/freedesktop-org] It is not for legislating formal standards.
[src:dbus-ipc/inter-process-communication] In computer science, **interprocess communication** (**IPC**) is the sharing of data between running processes in a computer system, or between multiple such systems.
[src:dbus-ipc/inter-process-communication] Mechanisms for IPC may be provided by an operating system.
[src:dbus-ipc/inter-process-communication] Applications which use IPC are often categorized as clients and servers, where the client requests data and the server responds to client requests.
[src:dbus-ipc/inter-process-communication] Many applications are both clients and servers, as commonly seen in distributed computing.
[src:dbus-ipc/inter-process-communication] IPC is very important to the design process for microkernels and nanokernels, which reduce the number of functionalities provided by the kernel.
[src:dbus-ipc/inter-process-communication] Those functionalities are then obtained by communicating with servers via IPC, leading to a large increase in communication when compared to a regular monolithic kernel.
[src:dbus-ipc/inter-process-communication] IPC interfaces generally encompass variable analytic framework structures.
[src:dbus-ipc/inter-process-communication] These processes ensure compatibility between the multi-vector protocols upon which IPC models rely.
[src:dbus-ipc/inter-process-communication] An IPC mechanism is either synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:dbus-ipc/inter-process-communication] Synchronization primitives may be used to have synchronous behavior with an asynchronous IPC mechanism.
[src:dbus-ipc/inter-process-communication] Merging data from two processes can often incur significantly higher costs compared to processing the same data on a single thread, potentially by two or more orders of magnitude due to overheads such as inter-process communication and synchronization.
[src:dbus-ipc/inter-process-communication] Different approaches to IPC have been tailored to different software requirements, such as performance, modularity, and system circumstances such as network bandwidth and latency.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-broker] A **message broker** (also known as an **integration broker** or **interface engine**) is an intermediary computer program module that translates a message from the formal messaging protocol of the sender to the formal messaging protocol of the receiver.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-broker] Message brokers are elements in telecommunication or computer networks where software applications communicate by exchanging formally defined messages.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-broker] Message brokers are a building block of message-oriented middleware (MOM) but are typically not a replacement for traditional middleware like MOM and remote procedure call (RPC).
[src:dbus-ipc/message-broker] A message broker is an architectural pattern for message validation, transformation, and routing.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-broker] It mediates communication among applications, minimizing the mutual awareness that applications should have of each other in order to be able to exchange messages, effectively implementing decoupling.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-broker] The primary purpose of a broker is to take incoming messages from applications and perform some action on them.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-broker] Message brokers can decouple end-points, meet specific non-functional requirements, and facilitate reuse of intermediary functions.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-broker] For example, a message broker may be used to manage a workload queue or message queue for multiple receivers, providing reliable storage, guaranteed message delivery and perhaps transaction management.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-broker] Message brokers are generally based on one of two fundamental architectures: hub-and-spoke and message bus.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-broker] In the first, a central server acts as the mechanism that provides integration services, whereas with the latter, the message broker is a communication backbone or distributed service that acts on the bus.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-broker] Additionally, a more scalable multi-hub approach can be used to integrate multiple brokers.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-broker] Message brokers that are purpose built to achieve time-bounded communications with end-to-end predictability allow for the development of real-time systems that require execution predictability.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] MOM allows application modules to be distributed over heterogeneous platforms and reduces the complexity of developing applications that span multiple operating systems and network protocols.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] The middleware creates a distributed communications layer that insulates the application developer from the details of the various operating systems and network interfaces.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Application programming interfaces (APIs) that extend across diverse platforms and networks are typically provided by MOM.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] This middleware layer allows software components (applications, servlets, and other components) that have been developed independently and might run on different networked platforms to interact with one another.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Applications distributed on different network nodes use the application interface to communicate.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] In addition, by providing an administrative interface, this new, virtual system of interconnected applications can be made fault tolerant and secure.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] MOM provides software elements that reside in all communicating components of a client/server architecture and typically support asynchronous calls between the client and server applications.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] MOM reduces the involvement of application developers with the complexity of the master-slave nature of the client/server mechanism.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] All these models make it possible for one software component to affect the behavior of another component over a network.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] They are different in that RPC- and ORB-based middleware create systems of tightly coupled components, whereas MOM-based systems allow for a loose coupling of components.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] In an RPC- or ORB-based system, when one procedure calls another, it must wait for the called procedure to return before it can do anything else.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] In these mostly synchronous messaging models, the middleware functions partly as a super-linker, locating the called procedure on a network and using network services to pass function or method parameters to the procedure and then to return results.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Note that Object request brokers also support fully asynchronous messaging via oneway invocations.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Central reasons for using a message-based communications protocol include its ability to store (buffer), route, or transform messages while conveying them from senders to receivers.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Another advantage of messaging provider-mediated messaging between clients is that by adding an administrative interface, you can monitor and tune performance.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Client applications are thus effectively relieved of every problem except that of sending, receiving, and processing messages.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] It is up to the code that implements the MOM system and up to the administrator to resolve issues like interoperability, reliability, security, scalability, and performance.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Using a MOM system, a client makes an API call to send a message to a destination managed by the provider.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] The call invokes provider services to route and deliver the message.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Once it has sent the message, the client can continue to do other work, confident that the provider retains the message until a receiving client retrieves it.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] The message-based model, coupled with the mediation of the provider, makes it possible to create a system of loosely coupled components.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] MOM comprises a category of inter-application communication software that generally relies on asynchronous message-passing, as opposed to a request-response architecture.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] In asynchronous systems, message queues provide temporary storage when the destination program is busy or not connected.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] In addition, most asynchronous MOM systems provide persistent storage to back up the message queue.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] This means that the sender and receiver do not need to connect to the network at the same time (asynchronous delivery), and problems with intermittent connectivity are solved.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] It also means that should the receiver application fail for any reason, the senders can continue unaffected, as the messages they send will simply accumulate in the message queue for later processing when the receiver restarts.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Many message-oriented middleware implementations depend on a message queue system.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Some implementations permit routing logic to be provided by the messaging layer itself, while others depend on client applications to provide routing information or allow for a mix of both paradigms.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Some implementations make use of broadcast or multicast distribution paradigms.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] In a message-based middleware system, the message received at the destination need not be identical to the message originally sent.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] A MOM system with built-in intelligence can transform messages and route to match the requirements of the sender or of the recipient.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] In conjunction with the routing and broadcast/multicast facilities, one application can send a message in its own native format, and two or more other applications may each receive a copy of the message in their own native format.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Many modern MOM systems provide sophisticated message transformation (or mapping) tools which allow programmers to specify transformation rules applicable to a simple GUI drag-and-drop operation.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] The primary disadvantage of many message-oriented middleware systems is that they require an extra component in the architecture, the message transfer agent (message broker).
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] As with any system, adding another component can lead to reductions in performance and reliability, and can also make the system as a whole more difficult and expensive to maintain.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] In addition, many inter-application communications have an intrinsically synchronous aspect, with the sender specifically wanting to wait for a reply to a message before continuing (see real-time computing and near-real-time for extreme cases).
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Because message-based communication inherently functions asynchronously, it may not fit well in such situations.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] That said, most MOM systems have facilities to group a request and a response as a single pseudo-synchronous transaction.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] With a synchronous messaging system, the calling function does not return until the called function has finished its task.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] In a loosely coupled asynchronous system, the calling client can continue to load work upon the recipient until the resources needed to handle this work are depleted and the called component fails.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Of course, these conditions can be minimized or avoided by monitoring performance and adjusting message flow, but this is work that is not needed with a synchronous messaging system.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] The important thing is to understand the advantages and liabilities of each kind of system.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Each system is appropriate for different kinds of tasks.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Sometimes, a combination of the two kinds of systems is required to obtain the desired behavior.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Historically, there was a lack of standards governing the use of message-oriented middleware that has caused problems.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Most of the major vendors have their own implementations, each with its own application programming interface (API) and management tools.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] One of the long-standing standards for message-oriented middleware is X/Open group's XATMI specification (Distributed Transaction Processing: The XATMI Specification) which standardizes API for interprocess communications.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Known implementations for this API is ATR Baltic's Enduro/X middleware and Oracle's Tuxedo.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] The Advanced Message Queuing Protocol (AMQP) is an approved OASIS and ISO standard that defines the protocol and formats used between participating application components, so implementations are interoperable.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] It also supports transaction management, queuing, distribution, security, management, clustering, federation and heterogeneous multi-platform support.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Java applications that use AMQP are typically written in Java JMS.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Other implementations provide APIs for C#, C++, PHP, Python, Ruby, and other programming languages.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] The High Level Architecture (HLA IEEE 1516) is an Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) and Simulation Interoperability Standards Organization (SISO) standard for simulation interoperability.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] It defines a set of services, provided through an API in C++ or Java.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] The services offer publish/subscribe-based information exchange, based on a modular Federation Object Model.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] There are also services for coordinated data exchange and time advance, based on logical simulation time, as well as synchronization points.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Additional services provide transfer of ownership, data distribution optimizations and monitoring and management of participating Federates (systems).
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] The MQ Telemetry Transport (MQTT) is an ISO standard (ISO/IEC PRF 20922) supported by the OASIS organization.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] It provides a lightweight publish/subscribe reliable messaging transport protocol on top of TCP/IP suitable for communication in M2M/IoT contexts where a small code footprint is required and/or network bandwidth is at a premium.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] The Object Management Group's Data Distribution Service (DDS) provides message-oriented Publish/Subscribe (P/S) middleware standard that aims to enable scalable, real-time, dependable, high-performance and interoperable data exchanges between publishers and subscribers.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] The standard provides interfaces to C++, C++11, C, Ada, Java, and Ruby.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] The eXtensible Messaging and Presence Protocol (XMPP) is a communications protocol for message-oriented middleware based on Extensible Markup Language (XML).
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Designed to be extensible, the protocol has also been used for publish-subscribe systems, signalling for VoIP, video, file transfer, gaming, Internet of Things applications such as the smart grid, and social networking services.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Unlike most instant messaging protocols, XMPP is defined in an open standard and uses an open systems approach of development and application, by which anyone may implement an XMPP service and interoperate with other organizations' implementations.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Because XMPP is an open protocol, implementations can be developed using any software license; although many server, client, and library implementations are distributed as free and open-source software, many freeware and proprietary software implementations also exist.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) formed an XMPP working group in 2002 to formalize the core protocols as an IETF instant messaging and presence technology.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] The XMPP Working group produced four specifications (RFC 3920, RFC 3921, RFC 3922, RFC 3923), which were approved as Proposed Standards in 2004.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] In 2011, RFC 3920 and RFC 3921 were superseded by RFC 6120 and RFC 6121 respectively, with RFC 6122 specifying the XMPP address format.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] In addition to these core protocols standardized at the IETF, the XMPP Standards Foundation (formerly Jabber Software Foundation) is active in developing open XMPP extensions.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] XMPP-based software is deployed widely across the Internet, according to the XMPP Standards Foundation, and forms the basis for the Department of Defense (DoD) Unified Capabilities Framework.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] A similar effort is with the actively evolving OpenMAMA project, which aims to provide a common API, especially to C clients.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] As of August 2012, it is mainly appropriate for distributing market-oriented data (e.g. stock quotes) over pub-sub middleware.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Message queues allow the exchange of information between distributed applications.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] A message queue can reside in memory or disk storage.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Messages stay in the queue until the time they are processed by a service consumer.
[src:dbus-ipc/message-oriented-middleware] Through the message queue, the application can be implemented independently - they do not need to know each other's position, or continue to implement procedures to remove the need for waiting to receive this message.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] That is, the programmer writes essentially the same code whether the subroutine is local to the executing program, or remote.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] This is a form of server interaction (caller is client, executor is server), typically implemented via a request–response message passing system.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] In the object-oriented programming paradigm, RPCs are represented by remote method invocation (RMI).
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] The RPC model implies a level of location transparency, namely that calling procedures are largely the same whether they are local or remote, but usually, they are not identical, so local calls can be distinguished from remote calls.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] Remote calls are usually orders of magnitude slower and less reliable than local calls, so distinguishing them is important.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] Many different (often incompatible) technologies have been used to implement the concept.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] Request–response protocols date to early distributed computing in the late 1960s, theoretical proposals of remote procedure calls as the model of network operations date to the 1970s, and practical implementations date to the early 1980s.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] Bruce Jay Nelson is generally credited with coining the term "remote procedure call" in 1981.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] Remote procedure calls used in modern operating systems trace their roots back to the RC 4000 multiprogramming system, which used a request-response communication protocol for process synchronization.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] The idea of treating network operations as remote procedure calls goes back at least to the 1970s in early ARPANET documents.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] In 1978, Per Brinch Hansen proposed Distributed Processes, a language for distributed computing based on "external requests" consisting of procedure calls between processes.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] One of the earliest practical implementations was in 1982 by Brian Randell and colleagues for their Newcastle Connection between UNIX machines.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] This was soon followed by "Lupine" by Andrew Birrell and Bruce Nelson in the Cedar environment at Xerox PARC.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] Lupine automatically generated stubs, providing type-safe bindings, and used an efficient protocol for communication.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] One of the first business uses of RPC was by Xerox under the name "Courier" in 1981.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] The first popular implementation of RPC on Unix was Sun's RPC (now called ONC RPC), used as the basis for Network File System (NFS).
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] In the 1990s, with the popularity of object-oriented programming, an alternative model of remote method invocation (RMI) was widely implemented, such as in Common Object Request Broker Architecture (CORBA, 1991) and Java remote method invocation.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] RMIs, in turn, fell in popularity with the rise of the internet, particularly in the 2000s.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] An RPC is initiated by the *client*, which sends a request message to a known remote *server* to execute a specified procedure with supplied parameters.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] The remote server sends a response to the client, and the application continues its process.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] While the server is processing the call, the client is blocked (it waits until the server has finished processing before resuming execution), unless the client sends an asynchronous request to the server, such as an XMLHttpRequest.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] There are many variations and subtleties in various implementations, resulting in a variety of different (incompatible) RPC protocols.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] An important difference between remote procedure calls and local calls is that remote calls can fail because of unpredictable network problems.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] Also, callers generally must deal with such failures without knowing whether the remote procedure was actually invoked.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] Idempotent procedures (those that have no additional effects if called more than once) are easily handled, but enough difficulties remain that code to call remote procedures is often confined to carefully written low-level subsystems.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] The client stub packs the parameters into a message and makes a system call to send the message.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] Packing the parameters is called marshalling.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] The client's local operating system sends the message from the client machine to the server machine.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] The local operating system on the server machine passes the incoming packets to the server stub.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] The server stub unpacks the parameters from the message.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] Unpacking the parameters is called unmarshalling.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] Finally, the server stub calls the server procedure.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] The reply traces the same steps in the reverse direction.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] To let different clients access servers, a number of standardized RPC systems have been created.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] Most of these use an interface description language (IDL) to let various platforms call the RPC.
[src:dbus-ipc/remote-procedure-call] The IDL files can then be used to generate code to interface between the client and servers.
